DESCRIPTION: Temporarily disconnect the control‑module chain and directly connect the PSU’s 12V and 0V output cables to the load module input cables (observing correct polarity). Insert the battery and measure the voltage at the load input and across the lamps to see if 12 V now appears and the lamp turns on.,
RESULT: The PSU Output Cable (+) to Load Input Cable (+) path shows an open circuit (≈7.23×10¹¹ Ω), while the PSU Output Cable (−) to Load Input Cable (−) path is resistive at 1.7 Ω. All measured voltages at the load input cables and both lamps are 0.0 V, and neither the main load lamp nor the internal indicator lamp is lit, with no observable internal faults.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:30:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['PSU Output Cable (+)', 'Load Input Cable (+)'] hypothesis_explanation='The direct‑bypass test where the control‑module chain was removed is decisive. When the PSU’s +12 V output cable was connected directly to the load module’s + input cable, the measured resistance from PSU (+) to Load (+) was ≈7.2×10¹¹ Ω (essentially open circuit), while the PSU (−) to Load (−) path measured only 1.7 Ω. With the battery inserted, there was 0.0 V at the load and across both lamps, even though both lamps have normal resistances and there is no polarity inversion or discontinuity in any of the control‑module interconnections.\n\nThis means the fault is not inside any control module or the load module; instead, the +12 V supply never actually reaches the load because the positive path between the power supply module and the load module is broken. Given the test setup, the only elements in that path are the PSU Output Cable (+) assembly and the Load Input Cable (+) assembly (including their fast‑connection terminals). One or both must be open (e.g., broken conductor, failed terminal crimp, or internal break inside the cable/connector). Repairing/replacing these cable/connector assemblies and re‑establishing a low‑resistance path for the +12 V line should restore correct operation of the lamp when the battery is inserted and the switches are ON.'
