2026-04-21 01:30:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['PSU Output Cable (−)', 'Load Input Cable (−)'] hypothesis_explanation='When the control‑module chain is bypassed and the PSU is wired directly to the load module, the measured resistance from PSU (+) to Load (+) is extremely high (≈7.2×10¹¹ Ω), while the PSU (−) to Load (−) path is only 1.7 Ω. We previously hypothesized that the positive path cables were open, but direct testing of the PSU internal 12 V node and its output cable (+) shows solid continuity and full voltage at the PSU side, and replacement of both PSU Output Cable (+) and Load Input Cable (+) had no effect. Therefore, the very high measured resistance on the positive path is most likely a measurement artifact caused by using the load module ground reference, which is not actually connected back to the PSU negative.\n\nAll modules and inter-module connections from control module 1 through to the load module have been checked: there are no polarity inversions and no opens along the nominal 12 V and 0 V conductors. The PSU LED lights (so local PSU negative and positive are connected), but no 12 V is ever observed at the load input—even when the control chain is bypassed and both lamps are known-good. The only remaining location where the circuit can be interrupted such that *everywhere in the load module remains at 0 V, the lamps show proper ohmic continuity, the diode is not yet proven faulty,* and yet the bypassed positive path appears open is on the return (0 V) side between the PSU and the load module.\n\nA fault (open/very high resistance) in either the PSU Output Cable (−) or the Load Input Cable (−) would break the reference return path so that all measurements at the load side with respect to the PSU negative show 0 V, even if the positive line were otherwise intact. This is consistent with the 1.7 Ω ‘resistive’ reading that may be due to leakage paths or measurement through other circuitry rather than a solid conductor. Consequently, the most plausible root cause is an open or severely degraded connection in the negative path between the PSU and the load module—specifically in either the PSU Output Cable (−) or the Load Input Cable (−).'
