2026-04-21 01:31:08 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Battery negative terminal contact / return path inside power supply module'] hypothesis_explanation='All continuity and polarity tests from PSU 12 V output through every control module to the load report intact conductors with no inversions and ≈0.1 Ω resistance, so the positive feed path is good. Bypassing the control chain and connecting PSU directly to the load still yields 0 V everywhere in the load module, yet the main and indicator lamps have normal resistance and the series diode has not been shown open. The PSU LED is on and the internal 12 V output node reads 12 V relative to the PSU 0 V reference, confirming the positive side up to the output cable is good.\n\nHowever, when measuring at the load (and even with the PSU connected directly to it), both lines read 0 V, which implies that the supposed 0 V reference being used in those measurements is actually floating and not the same as the PSU’s true negative terminal. The earlier tests that reported 0.0 V across the load, combined with huge apparent resistance on the positive path when the PSU and load were directly linked, are consistent with the load circuit’s return path to the battery negative being open somewhere internal to the PSU module—most likely at the battery’s negative terminal contact or its immediate connection to the PSU’s 0 V node.\n\nWith the battery negative not actually bonded into the external 0 V line, the battery still lights the PSU LED (because that LED and its resistor are wired locally across the battery terminals), so the PSU indicator appears normal. But the entire external chain (control modules and load) is effectively floating and sees no completed circuit, giving 0 V everywhere in that loop and preventing current through the lamps even when all switches are ON. Therefore the single most consistent root cause is an open or faulty connection at the battery negative terminal or its internal tie to the external 0 V output in the power‑supply module, i.e., a failed return path inside the PSU module rather than any of the external cables or downstream modules.'
